83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
HOUSE AMENDMENTS TO
HOUSE BILL 4139
By COMMITTEE ON ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT, SMALL BUSINESS, AND TRADE
February 16
1 On page 1 of the printed bill, line 2, after “cannabis;” delete the rest of the line and delete lines
2 3 through 5 and insert “amending ORS 475C.728 and 475C.777; repealing ORS 475C.913; and pre-
3 scribing an effective date.”.
4 Delete lines 7 through 21 and delete pages 2 through 20 and insert:
5 “SECTION 1. ORS 475C.728 is amended to read:
6 “475C.728. Notwithstanding ORS 475C.726, before making any other distribution from the
7 Oregon Marijuana Account established under ORS 475C.726, the Department of Revenue shall first
8 distribute quarterly from the account the following:
9 “(1) $875,000 to the Oregon Liquor and Cannabis Commission for deposit in the Marijuana
10 Control and Regulation Fund established under ORS 475C.297; and
11 “(2) [$750,000] $3 million to the Oregon Criminal Justice Commission for deposit into the Illegal
12 Marijuana Market Enforcement Grant Program Fund established under ORS 475C.535 for the pur-
13 poses of paying the costs incurred by the commission in carrying out the provisions of ORS
14 475C.531.
15 “SECTION 2. ORS 475C.777 is amended to read:
16 “475C.777. As used in ORS 475C.770 to 475C.919:
17 “(1) ‘Attending provider’ means one of the following health care providers who has primary re-
18 sponsibility for the care and treatment of a person diagnosed with a debilitating medical condition:
19 “(a) A physician licensed under ORS chapter 677;
20 “(b) A physician associate licensed under ORS 677.505 to 677.525;
21 “(c) A nurse practitioner licensed under ORS 678.375 to 678.390;
22 “(d) A clinical nurse specialist licensed under ORS 678.370 and 678.372;
23 “(e) A certified registered nurse anesthetist as defined in ORS 678.010; or
24 “(f) A naturopathic physician licensed under ORS chapter 685.
25 “(2) ‘Cannabinoid’ means any of the chemical compounds that are the active constituents of
26 marijuana.
27 “(3) ‘Cannabinoid concentrate’ means a substance obtained by separating cannabinoids from
28 marijuana by:
29 “(a) A mechanical extraction process;
30 “(b) A chemical extraction process using a nonhydrocarbon-based solvent, such as vegetable
31 glycerin, vegetable oils, animal fats, isopropyl alcohol or ethanol;
32 “(c) A chemical extraction process using the hydrocarbon-based solvent carbon dioxide, provided
33 that the process does not involve the use of high heat or pressure; or
34 “(d) Any other process identified by the Oregon Health Authority, in consultation with the
35 Oregon Liquor and Cannabis Commission, by rule.
LC 6/HB 4139-3

1 “(4) ‘Cannabinoid edible’ means food or potable liquid into which a cannabinoid concentrate,
2 cannabinoid extract or dried leaves or flowers of marijuana have been incorporated.
3 “(5) ‘Cannabinoid extract’ means a substance obtained by separating cannabinoids from
4 marijuana by:
5 “(a) A chemical extraction process using a hydrocarbon-based solvent, such as butane, hexane
6 or propane;
7 “(b) A chemical extraction process using the hydrocarbon-based solvent carbon dioxide, if the
8 process uses high heat or pressure; or
9 “(c) Any other process identified by the Oregon Health Authority, in consultation with the
10 Oregon Liquor and Cannabis Commission, by rule.
11 “(6) ‘Debilitating medical condition’ means:
12 “(a) Cancer, glaucoma, a degenerative or pervasive neurological condition, positive status for
13 human immunodeficiency virus or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, or a side effect related to
14 the treatment of those medical conditions;
15 “(b) A medical condition or treatment for a medical condition that produces, for a specific pa-
16 tient, one or more of the following:
17 “(A) Cachexia;
18 “(B) Severe pain;
19 “(C) Severe nausea;
20 “(D) Seizures, including seizures caused by epilepsy; or
21 “(E) Persistent muscle spasms, including spasms caused by multiple sclerosis;
22 “(c) Post-traumatic stress disorder; or
23 “(d) Any other medical condition or side effect related to the treatment of a medical condition
24 [adopted by the Oregon Health Authority by rule or approved by the authority pursuant to a petition
25 filed under ORS 475C.913] that an attending provider determines, in accordance with
26 evidence-based practice and professional judgment, might be mitigated by the medical use
27 of marijuana.
28 “(7)(a) ‘Delivery’ has the meaning given that term in ORS 475.005.
29 “(b) ‘Delivery’ does not include transfer of marijuana by a registry identification cardholder to
30 another registry identification cardholder if no consideration is paid for the transfer.
31 “(8)(a) ‘Designated primary caregiver’ means an individual:
32 “(A) Who is 18 years of age or older;
33 “(B) Who has significant responsibility for managing the well-being of a person who has been
34 diagnosed with a debilitating medical condition; and
35 “(C) Who is designated as the person responsible for managing the well-being of a person who
36 has been diagnosed with a debilitating medical condition on that person’s application for a registry
37 identification card or in other written notification submitted to the authority.
38 “(b) ‘Designated primary caregiver’ does not include a person’s attending provider.
39 “(9) ‘High heat’ means a temperature exceeding 180 degrees.
40 “(10) ‘Immature marijuana plant’ means a marijuana plant that is not flowering.
41 “(11)(a) ‘Marijuana’ means the plant Cannabis family Cannabaceae, any part of the plant
42 Cannabis family Cannabaceae and the seeds of the plant Cannabis family Cannabaceae.
43 “(b) ‘Marijuana’ does not include:
44 “(A) Industrial hemp, as defined in ORS 571.269; or
45 “(B) Prescription drugs, as that term is defined in ORS 689.005, including those containing one
HA to HB 4139 Page 2

1 or more cannabinoids, that are approved by the United States Food and Drug Administration and
2 dispensed by a pharmacy, as defined in ORS 689.005.
3 “(12) ‘Marijuana grow site’ means a location registered under ORS 475C.792 where marijuana
4 is produced for use by a registry identification cardholder.
5 “(13) ‘Marijuana processing site’ means a marijuana processing site registered under ORS
6 475C.815 or a site for which an applicant has submitted an application for registration under ORS
7 475C.815.
8 “(14) ‘Mature marijuana plant’ means a marijuana plant that is not an immature marijuana
9 plant.
10 “(15)(a) ‘Medical cannabinoid product’ means a cannabinoid edible and any other product in-
11 tended for human consumption or use, including a product intended to be applied to a person’s skin
12 or hair, that contains cannabinoids or dried leaves or flowers of marijuana.
13 “(b) ‘Medical cannabinoid product’ does not include:
14 “(A) Usable marijuana by itself;
15 “(B) A cannabinoid concentrate by itself;
16 “(C) A cannabinoid extract by itself; or
17 “(D) Industrial hemp, as defined in ORS 571.269.
18 “(16) ‘Medical marijuana dispensary’ means a medical marijuana dispensary registered under
19 ORS 475C.833 or a site for which an applicant has submitted an application for registration under
20 ORS 475C.833.
21 “(17) ‘Medical use of marijuana’ means the production, processing, possession, delivery or ad-
22 ministration of marijuana, or use of paraphernalia used to administer marijuana, to mitigate the
23 symptoms or effects of a debilitating medical condition.
24 “(18) ‘Person designated to produce marijuana by a registry identification cardholder’ means a
25 person designated to produce marijuana by a registry identification cardholder under ORS 475C.792
26 who produces marijuana for a registry identification cardholder at an address other than the address
27 where the registry identification cardholder resides or at an address where more than 12 mature
28 marijuana plants are produced.
29 “(19) ‘Process’ means the compounding or conversion of marijuana into medical cannabinoid
30 products, cannabinoid concentrates or cannabinoid extracts.
31 “(20) ‘Production’ means:
32 “(a) Planting, cultivating, growing, trimming or harvesting marijuana; or
33 “(b) Drying marijuana leaves or flowers.
34 “(21) ‘Registry identification card’ means a document issued by the Oregon Health Authority
35 under ORS 475C.783 that identifies a person authorized to engage in the medical use of marijuana
36 and, if the person has a designated primary caregiver under ORS 475C.789, the person’s designated
37 primary caregiver.
38 “(22) ‘Registry identification cardholder’ means a person to whom a registry identification card
39 has been issued under ORS 475C.783.
40 “(23)(a) ‘Usable marijuana’ means the dried leaves and flowers of marijuana.
41 “(b) ‘Usable marijuana’ does not include:
42 “(A) The seeds, stalks and roots of marijuana; or
43 “(B) Waste material that is a by-product of producing marijuana.
44 “(24) ‘Written documentation’ means a statement signed by the attending provider of a person
45 diagnosed with a debilitating medical condition or copies of the person’s relevant medical records.
